# Supermemory: PriceOfElectricity (POE)

This project has a dedicated Supermemory space. Use it for cross-session agent context.

## Space scoping

- This project uses the project-scoped Supermemory MCP server
  **`project-0-priceofelectricity-supermemory`**. That server is already
  scoped to the POE space, so the `memory` and `recall` tools do not need
  (and do not accept) a `containerTag` argument.
- The legacy `supermemory` MCP server (the global one) is also scoped to
  POE in this repo via `.cursor/mcp.json` (`x-sm-project: "priceofelectricity"`).
  If you ever fall back to that server, prefer the project-scoped one above.

## Start of session

- For non-trivial work, call `recall` early to load prior context
  (decisions, conventions, recent changes, open threads).

## End of each session (REQUIRED)

There is a Cursor hook at `.cursor/hooks/supermemory-end-of-session.js` that
fires on the trigger phrase **"end of session"** and injects a system reminder
telling you to run this protocol. Even when the hook does not fire (e.g. the
user wraps up with different wording like "done", "thanks", "bye", "that's
all", or explicitly asks to save/back up), you must still run the protocol
yourself.

The protocol:

1. Use the `memory` tool on `project-0-priceofelectricity-supermemory` with
   `action: "save"` and a single `content` string that summarizes this
   session.
2. The summary must capture:
   - What the user asked for this session
   - What changed (files touched, commands run, decisions made, and any
     commit SHAs and titles)
   - Current state and verification results (typecheck/build/verify outcomes,
     deploy status, open PRs)
   - Open items or deliberate follow-ups
3. Keep it factual and concise — aim for a focused list of short bullets or
   sentences. Do not paste large code blocks.
4. Do not save secrets, API keys, tokens, or `.env` values. Treat repo files
   and git state as the source of truth; memories are supplementary context,
   not overrides.
5. After the save call returns, briefly confirm to the user what was saved
   and surface any deferred follow-ups in your response. If the save fails,
   surface the error to the user instead of silently continuing.

## Trigger phrase

The literal phrase **"end of session"** is the canonical way to invoke this
protocol. The hook recognizes minor variants (`end-of-session`,
`end_of_session`, trailing punctuation, surrounding whitespace) but not free
paraphrases — those rely on this rule.
